              <span id="reviewTextContainer2449459019" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5338926712226235339">Back when Burrough&apos;s completed his anecdotal play-by-play account of the buyout of RJR Nabisco, it was suggested the book was considered for the most part an oddity, before becoming one of the least regarded but most recommended texts for business school applicants globally. Needless to say, ‘over-commitments&apos; and &apos;capital calls’ are considered part of the fund-industry lexicon nowadays. Here is a book with interesting insights likely more so for its applications to behavioural economics rather </span>
  <span id="freeText5338926712226235339" style="display:none">Back when Burrough's completed his anecdotal play-by-play account of the buyout of RJR Nabisco, it was suggested the book was considered for the most part an oddity, before becoming one of the least regarded but most recommended texts for business school applicants globally. Needless to say, ‘over-commitments' and 'capital calls’ are considered part of the fund-industry lexicon nowadays. Here is a book with interesting insights likely more so for its applications to behavioural economics rather than to corporate finance, at least for me. By no means a perfect business text as it's somewhat whimsical; however this adds much to the work.</span>
