<div id="review_1454859893" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1454859893" />
    <a title="Nikolaos" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30038458-nikolaos"><img alt="Nikolaos" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1422567440p2/30038458.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1454859893?book_show_action=true">Nov 29, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nikolaos" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nikolaos" href="/user/show/30038458-nikolaos">Nikolaos</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Business students</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1454859893" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8468272886995433573">I have not read such an exciting business book for a while. &quot;Barbarians&quot; is an outstanding account on the insights of the LBO world, written by two reporters with an appetite for refined ridiculousness. I was amazed at the relevance of the reported absurdities with contemporary criticism on Big Finance, though nowadays the spotlight was set on proprietary and algorithmic trading.<br/><br/>If you are into business case studies or just historical accounts of grand corporate events, this book is for you.</span>
  <span id="freeText8468272886995433573" style="display:none">I have not read such an exciting business book for a while. "Barbarians" is an outstanding account on the insights of the LBO world, written by two reporters with an appetite for refined ridiculousness. I was amazed at the relevance of the reported absurdities with contemporary criticism on Big Finance, though nowadays the spotlight was set on proprietary and algorithmic trading.<br /><br />If you are into business case studies or just historical accounts of grand corporate events, this book is for you.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8468272886995433573" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
